rd]] [[Ford Sigma engine|Sigma 1.6L]] and [[Mazda L engine|L 2.0L]]-engine with [[Direct Injection Spark Ignition]]\n* 2013&ndash;present '''[[Ford Ecoboost engine|Ecoboost]]'''&mdash;1.5 [[Ford]]\n* 2016&ndash;present [[EcoBlue]]&mdash;[[Diesel engine|Diesel]]\n\n==5 Cylinder==\n* 2015\u2013present; The 3.2 is an I5 engine used in the Ford Transit, the Ford Ranger, Ford Everest, Mazda BT-50 and the Vivarail. For the North American-spec Transit, * the 3.2L Duratorq is modified to meet American and Canadian emissions standards and is branded as a Power Stroke engine. The 3.2 Power Stroke is rated 188 PS (138&nbsp;kW; 185&nbsp;hp) and 470 N\u22c5m (350&nbsp;lb\u22c5ft).[8]\n\n==6 cylinder==\nFord was late to offer a six-cylinder engine in their cars, only introducing a six in 1941 after the failure of the 1906 [[Ford Model K|Model K]]. The company relied on its famous [[Ford Flathead engine|Flathead V8]] for most models, only seriously producing six-cylinder engines in the 1960s. The company was also late with a [[V6 engine]], introducing a compact British V6 in 1967 but waiting until the 1980s to move their products to rely on V6 engines. The company has relied on six major V6 families ever since, the [[Ford Cologne V6 engine|Cologne/Taunus V6]], [[Ford Essex V6 engine (UK)|Essex V6]], [[Ford Essex V6 engine (Canadian)|Canadian Essex V6]], [[Ford Vulcan V6 engine|Vulcan V6]], [[Ford Mondeo engine|Mondeo V6]] and [[Ford Cyclone engine|Cyclone V6]]. The first three of these lines are no longer in production, leaving only the [[Ford Mondeo V6 engine|Mondeo]] and [[Ford Cyclone engine|Cyclone]] as the company's midrange engines.\n* 1906&ndash;1907 '''Model K straight-6'''\n* 1941&ndash;2016 '''[[Ford Straight-6 engine|Straight-6]]'''\n** 1941&ndash;1951 226&nbsp;[[Cubic inch|CID]] ''Flathead''\n** 1948&ndash;1953 254&nbsp;CID ''Flathead'' used in buses and two ton trucks\n** 1952&ndash;1964 [[Overhead valve|OHV]] (215, 223, 262) 215-223 used in car and non-HD pickups. 262 used in HD trucks only.\n[[Image:Ford 144cid six cylinder.jpg|thumb|right|180px|144&nbsp;CID [[straight-6]] in a 1964 [[Ford Falcon (North America)|Ford Falcon]]]]\n** 1960&ndash;1993 (Longer in [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Australia]]) 'Falcon Six' [[Overhead valve|OHV]] (144, 170, 200, 250) car usage.\n** 1964&ndash;1996 [[Overhead valve|OHV]] (240, 300, 4.9&nbsp;L) truck 6 built in [[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n** 1988&ndash;2002 [[Ford Australia]] [[SOHC]] [[Straight-six engine|I6]] [[Ford Falcon (Australia)|Falcon]] engines\n*** 1988&ndash;1989 3.2&nbsp;L [[SOHC]]\n*** 1988&ndash;1992 3.9&nbsp;L [[SOHC]]\n*** 1992&ndash;2002 4.0&nbsp;L [[SOHC]]\n*** 1998&ndash;2002 4.0&nbsp;L [[SOHC]] VCT\n** 2002&ndash;2016 [[Ford Australia]] [[Ford Barra engine|Barra]] [[DOHC]] [[Straight-six engine|I6]] 4.0&nbsp;L engines\n* 1951&ndash;1966 '''[[Ford Zephyr engine|Zephyr 6]]'''&mdash;([[United Kingdom]])\n* 1966&ndash;1988 (2000 in South Africa) '''[[Ford Essex V6 engine (UK)|British Essex V6]]'''&mdash;60\u00b0 British V6 2.5/3.0/3.1/3.4&nbsp;L\n* 1964&ndash;2011 '''[[Ford Cologne V6 engine|Cologne/Taunus V6]]'''&mdash;1.8&ndash;4.0&nbsp;L [[pushrod]] and [[SOHC]] V6\n* 1982&ndash;2008 '''[[Ford Essex V6 engine (Canadian)|Canadian Essex V6]]'''&mdash;90\u00b0 V6, 3.8/3.9/4.2&nbsp;L models\n* 1986&ndash;1992 '''[[Ford Cologne V6 engine|Cologne/Ranger, Bronco II V6]] &mdash;''' 2.8/2.9/4.0OHV/4.0SOHC&nbsp;L\n* 1986&ndash;2007 '''[[Ford Vulcan engine|Vulcan V6]]'''&mdash;60\u00b0 [[pushrod]] V6 3.0&nbsp;L, originally designed for the [[Ford Taurus|Taurus]]\n* 1989&ndash;1995 '''[[Ford SHO V6 engine|SHO V6]]''' 3.0/3.2&nbsp;L [[DOHC]] V6\n* 1994&ndash;2012 '''[[Ford Duratec V6 engine|Mondeo V6]]''' aluminum 60\u00b0 [[DOHC]]\n** 1994&ndash;2002 '''[[Ford Duratec engine#Duratec 25 2|Duratec 25]]'''&mdash;2.5&nbsp;L\n** 1996&ndash;2012 '''[[Ford Duratec engine#Duratec 30|Duratec 30]]'''&mdash;3.0&nbsp;L\n** 2000&ndash;2011 '''[[Jaguar AJ-V6 engine|Jaguar AJ-V6]]'''&mdash;3.0&nbsp;L\n* 2003&ndash;present '''[[Ford Ecotorq engine|Ecotorq]]'''&mdash;7.3/9.0/12.7&nbsp;L [[Diesel engine|Diesel]]\n* 2004&ndash;present '''[[Ford AJD-V6/PSA DT17|AJD-V6]]'''&mdash;2.7&nbsp;L [[Diesel engine|Diesel]]\n* 2006&ndash;2016 '''[[Volvo SI6 engine|SI6]]'''&mdash;3.0/3.2&nbsp;L [[Straight-six engine|I6]] designed by [[Volvo Cars|Volvo]]{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n* 2006&ndash;present '''[[Ford Cyclone engine|Cyclone V6]]''' aluminum 60\u00b0 [[DOHC]]\n** 2018 '''[[Ford Cyclone engine#3.3 L|Duratec 33]]'''&mdash;3.3&nbsp;L\n** 2006&ndash;present '''[[Ford Duratec engine#Duratec 35|Duratec 35]]'''&mdash;3.5&nbsp;L\n** 2007&ndash;present '''[[Ford Duratec engine#Duratec 37|Duratec 37]]'''&mdash;3.7&nbsp;L\n*2009&ndash;present '''[[Ford EcoBoost engine|EcoBoost V6 engine]]\n** 2015&ndash;present '''[[Ford EcoBoost engine#2.7-L|EcoBoost]]'''&mdash;2.7&nbsp;L\n** 2016&ndash;present '''[[Ford EcoBoost engine#3.0-L|EcoBoost]]'''&mdash;3.0&nbsp;L\n** 2009&ndash;present '''[[Ford EcoBoost engine#3.5-L|EcoBoost]]'''&mdash;3.5&nbsp;L\n\n==8 cylinder==\n{{redirect2|Ford V-8|Ford V8|Ford's first mass-produced car with a V-8 engine|1932 Ford}}\nFord introduced the [[Ford flathead V8 engine|Flathead V8]] in their affordable [[1932 Ford|1932 Model 18]], becoming a performance leader for decades. In the 1950s, Ford introduced a three-tier approach to engines, with small, mid-sized, and larger engines aimed at different markets. All of Ford's mainstream V8 engines were replaced by the [[overhead cam]] [[Ford Modular engine|Modular family]] in the 1990s and the company introduced a new large architecture, the [[Ford Boss engine|Boss family]], for 2010.\n* 1920&ndash;1932 '''[[Lincoln Liberty engine|Lincoln 60 Degree Fork & Blade V8]]'''&mdash;({{convert|357.8|and|384.8|cid|L|1|abbr=on}})\n* 1932&ndash;1953 '''[[Ford flathead V8 engine|Flathead V8]]'''\n* 1940&ndash;1950 '''[[Ford GAA engine]]''', exclusively for [[armored fighting vehicle]] military use \n* 1952&ndash;1963 '''[[Lincoln Y-block V8 engine]]'''&mdash;[[big-block]] (317/341/368), HD truck (279/302/317/332)\n* 1954&ndash;1964 '''[[Ford Y-block engine|Y-block V8]]'''&mdash;[[small-block]] Ford/Mercury/Edsel (239/256/272/292/312)\n* 1958&ndash;1968 '''[[Ford MEL engine|MEL V8]]'''&mdash;big-block Mercury/Edsel/Lincoln (383/410/430/462)\n* 1958&ndash;1976 '''[[Ford FE engine|FE V8]]'''&mdash;[[Mid block|medium-block]] Ford/Edsel\n** 1958&ndash;1971 Generation I (332/352/360/361/390)\n** 1962&ndash;1973 Generation II (406/410/427/428)\n** 1965&ndash;1968 [[Ford 427 side oiler]]\n** FT truck (330/359/361/389/391)\n** 427 SOHC**\n* 1958&ndash;1981 '''[[Ford Super Duty engine|Super Duty truck engine]]'''&mdash;big-block (401/477/534)\n* 1962&ndash;2000 '''[[Ford Windsor engine|Windsor]]'''&mdash;small-block (221/255/260/289/289HP/302/351W/[[Ford Boss 302 engine|Boss 302]]/427 aluminum)\n* 1968&ndash;1997 '''[[Ford 385 engine|385 V8]]'''&mdash;big-block (370/429/[[Boss 429]]/460/514)\n* 1970&ndash;1982 '''[[Ford 335 engine|335/Cleveland V8]]'''&mdash; small-block (351 Cleveland/400/351M/[[Ford Boss 351 engine|Boss 351]])\n** 1972&ndash;1985 '''[[Ford Australia]]''' produced Cleveland V8 engines 302/351 ([[Geelong]] plant)\n* 1983&ndash;2010 '''Ford/[[Navistar]] [[Diesel engine|Diesel]] V8'''\n** 1983&ndash;1987&mdash;6.9&nbsp;L [[International Harvester IDI|IDI (indirect injection)]]\n** 1988&ndash;1993&mdash;7.3&nbsp;L IDI\n** 1993&ndash;1994.5&mdash;7.3&nbsp;L IDI with Turbo\n** 1994.5&ndash;2003.5&mdash;7.3&nbsp;L DI (direct injection) \"[[Ford Power Stroke engine|Power Stroke]]\"\n** 2003.5&ndash;2009&mdash;6.0&nbsp;L DI \"Power Stroke\" (E and F-series vehicles)\n** 2008&ndash;2010&mdash;6.4&nbsp;L DI \"Power Stroke\" (F-series only)\n* 1991&ndash;present '''[[Ford Modular engine|Modular V8]]''' &mdash;[[Overhead camshaft|SOHC]]/DOHC 4.6/5.0/5.4/5.8&nbsp;L\n** 1997&ndash;present '''Triton V8'''&mdash;truck versions of the Modular\n** 2003-2004 '''[[Ford Modular engine#4.6.Terminator|Terminator V8]]''' DOHC Supercharged 4.6 L\n** 2011&ndash;present '''[[Ford Modular engine#5.0.C2.A0L Coyote|Coyote V8]]''' &mdash;[[Overhead camshaft#Double overhead camshaft|DOHC]] [[Variable Cam Timing (Ford)|TiVCT]] 5.0&nbsp;L\n* 1996&ndash;present '''[[Jaguar AJ-V8 engine|Jaguar AJ-V8]]'''&mdash;small displacement [[DOHC]] V8 engine family also used by [[Lincoln LS]] and [[Ford Thunderbird]]\n* 1996&ndash;1999 '''[[Ford SHO V8 engine|SHO V8]]'''&mdash;3.4&nbsp;L DOHC 60\u00b0 V8 designed and produced with [[Yamaha Motor Corporation]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}} This engine was only used in the Taurus SHO V-8.\n* 2005&ndash;2010 '''[[Volvo B8444S engine|Volvo V8]]'''&mdash;4.4&nbsp;L DOHC 60\u00b0 V8 produced by Yamaha Motor Company in Japan in connection with Volvo Sk\u00f6vde Engine plant Sweden.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n* '''[[Cosworth Ford DFV|Cosworth DFV]]'''&mdash;DOHC 3.0 liter racing engine\n* 2006&ndash;present '''[[Jaguar AJD-V6 engine|AJD-V8]]'''&mdash;DOHC 3.6&nbsp;L twin-turbo [[Diesel engine|Diesel]]\n* 2010&ndash;present '''[[Ford 4.4 Turbo Diesel|4.4 Turbo Diesel V8]]'''&mdash;DOHC 4.4&nbsp;L twin-turbo Diesel\n* 2010&ndash;present '''[[Ford Boss engine|Boss V8]]'''&mdash;[[Overhead camshaft|SOHC]] 6.2&nbsp;L\n* 2010&ndash;present Coyote V8 Engine. In 2018 dual fuel injection added providing both port and direct injection. Horspower estimated to be over 450HP and Torque estimated at over 425\n* 2011&ndash;present '''[[Ford Power Stroke#6.7 Scorpion|Scorpion Diesel V8]]'''&mdash;\"Power Stroke\" [[Overhead valve|OHV]] 6.7&nbsp;L 32-valve DI turbo diesel (F-series only)\n* 2013&ndash;2014 '''[[Ford Modular engine#5.8 L Trinity|Trinity V8]]''' 5.8&nbsp;L, supercharged (Shelby GT500)\n* 2016&ndash;present '''[[5.2 L \"Voodoo\" V8|Voodoo V8]]''' &mdash;[[Overhead camshaft|DOHC]] 5.2&nbsp;L (Shelby GT350)\n* 2020&ndash;present '''[[Ford Modular engine#Predator|Predator V8]]''' &mdash;[[Overhead camshaft|DOHC]] 5.2&nbsp;L, supercharged (Shelby GT500)\n*2020&ndash;present Godzilla V8  &mdash;  Pushrod V8 7.3L (445ci), gasoline, naturally aspirated, port fuel injected, variable timing, 16valve, 10.5:1 compression made for F-series Super Duty models.\n\n==10 cylinder==\n* 1997&ndash;present '''[[Ford Modular engine#6.8.C2.A0L V10|Triton V10]]'''&mdash;6.8L SOHC 90\u00b0 Modular [[V10 engine|V10]] truck engine\n* 2001 5.8L DOHC 54\u00b0 Modular V10, 4 valves/cyl. (Experimental). Ford Powertrain Division.\n\n==12 cylinder==\n* 1932&ndash;1942 '''[[Lincoln L-head V12 engine|Lincoln L-head V12]]''' (382/414/448)\n* 1936&ndash;1948 '''[[Lincoln-Zephyr V12 engine|Lincoln-Zephyr V12]]''' (267/292/306)\n* 1941 '''[[Ford GAA engine|Ford V-12 aero engine]]'''\n* 1941 '''[[Ford GAA engine|Ford GAA V12]]'''\n* 1999 - Current '''[[Ford Duratec V6 engine#5.9 L V12|Aston Martin 6.0L V12]]''' (Originally made by Aston Martin under Ford ownership, continued by Aston Martin to present day.)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Ford cars]]\n* [[List of Ford platforms]]\n* [[List of Ford bellhousing patterns]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.302w.com/ Website & Forums dedicated to the Ford Windsor Engine]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050518000641/http://www.fordclassics.com/enginespecs.html Specs on Ford overhead valve V8 engines]\n\n{{Ford Motor Company}}\n{{Ford v8 engines}}\n{{Ford modern v8 engines}}\n\n[[Category:Ford engines| ]]\n[[Category:Ford Motor Company|Engines]]\n[[Category:Lists of engines|Ford]]\n", "name_user": "Sable232", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:HEADINGS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Ford_engines"}
